---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SubNav from '../components/SubNav.astro';
import ResourceLibrary from '../components/ResourceLibrary.astro';

const subnavSections = [
  { id: 'amtrak', label: 'Risk' },
  { id: 'precedent', label: 'Precedent' },
  { id: 'site', label: 'Site' },
  { id: 'funding', label: 'Funding' },
  { id: 'library', label: 'Sources' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Claymont to Fox Point | Project Brief"
  description="Project brief for Fox Point Cove: climate risk along the rail line, a clear shoreline restoration plan, and the early work needed to unlock about $5.03M already tied to the site."
  canonical="https://fox-point-riverwalk.vercel.app/"
  ogImageAlt="Aerial concept rendering of the Claymont-to-Fox-Point corridor: Delaware River, living-shoreline boardwalk, Amtrak train along the Northeast Corridor, and I-495."
  preloadHero={true}
>
  <Fragment slot="hero">
    <div class="hero-fullbleed">
      <img
        src="/assets/hero-claymont-to-fox-point-state-park.jpg"
        alt="Aerial concept rendering of the Claymont-to-Fox-Point corridor: Delaware River on the left, a living shoreline trail and boardwalk with people walking and biking, an Amtrak train along the Northeast Corridor rail line, and I-495 to the right"
        class="hero-fb-photo"
        width="1920"
        height="1080"
        fetchpriority="high"
      />
      <div class="hero-fb-overlay"></div>
      <div class="hero-fb-content">
        <section class="hero-copy hero-copy-light">
          <p class="kicker kicker-light">Project Brief</p>
          <h1>Help reconnect Claymont to a cleaner, safer shoreline.</h1>
          <p class="lede lede-light">
            The first phase — restoring Fox Point Cove — already has $5M in pledges and a state plan.
            What is still needed is the early work that turns that plan into permits and shovels.
            Long-term, the vision continues the shoreline north to the Claymont Transit Center.
          </p>
          <div class="hero-points hero-points-light">
            <span>$5.03M already tied to the site</span>
            <span>State plan in place</span>
            <span>203 river acres</span>
            <span>Early project work is the gap</span>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>
      <div class="hero-fb-chips" aria-hidden="true">
        <span>Delaware River →</span>
        <span>Living shoreline</span>
        <span>Rail line</span>
        <span>← Port of Edgemoor</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="skim-band" aria-label="Executive skim">
      <article class="skim-card">
        <p class="skim-title">Amtrak already documents the risk.</p>
        <p class="skim-copy">Fox Point sits beside a part of the Northeast Corridor where flooding risk and delay costs are already well documented.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="skim-card">
        <p class="skim-title">The site and the plan are already clear.</p>
        <p class="skim-copy">The site boundary, the state plan, and DNREC oversight make this easier to move than a project starting from scratch.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="skim-card">
        <p class="skim-title">Pay for the work that gets the project ready.</p>
        <p class="skim-copy">The gap is design, permits, planning, and people working together to turn a strong idea into a real project.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="skim-card">
        <p class="skim-title">$5.03M can move faster with the right early work.</p>
        <p class="skim-copy">This would not create demand from scratch. It would help existing dollars move toward a project people can actually build.</p>
      </article>
    </section>
  </Fragment>

  <SubNav slot="subnav" sections={subnavSections} />

  <main id="main-content" tabindex="-1">
    <section class="panel risk-section" id="amtrak">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div>
          <p class="section-label">Risk</p>
          <h2>Fox Point is the Northeast Corridor's most vulnerable shoreline.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="section-copy">Wilmington is sinking faster than any other shoreline on the Northeast Corridor, and the Delaware River is rising. Fox Point sits where those pressures meet the rail line, and Amtrak has already recorded the cost.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-big-row">
        <article class="risk-stat-card">
          <p class="risk-number">$127M</p>
          <p class="risk-label">Losses already recorded</p>
          <p class="risk-sub">Delay and revenue costs · 2006–2019</p>
          <div class="risk-bar-track">
            <div class="risk-bar-fill rfill-84"></div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="risk-stat-card">
          <p class="risk-number">450+</p>
          <p class="risk-label">Storm-related disruptions</p>
          <p class="risk-sub">2006–2019 · Northeast Corridor</p>
          <div class="risk-bar-track">
            <div class="risk-bar-fill rfill-full"></div>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="risk-stat-card risk-hot-card">
          <p class="risk-number">$220M</p>
          <p class="risk-label">Possible future losses</p>
          <p class="risk-sub">Next decade · if nothing changes</p>
          <div class="risk-gradient-bar"></div>
        </article>
      </div>

      <div class="trio-grid">
        <article class="weather-card wc-rain">
          <p class="wc-title">Heavy storms are almost twice as common as they were in 1960.</p>
          <div class="wc-rows">
            <div class="wc-row">
              <span class="wc-year">1960s</span>
              <div class="dot-strip">
                <span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span>
              </div>
              <span class="wc-count">5×</span>
            </div>
            <div class="wc-row wc-row-now">
              <span class="wc-year">Today</span>
              <div class="dot-strip">
                <span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span>
                <span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span>
              </div>
              <span class="wc-count">10×</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="wc-stat-num">+92%</p>
          <p class="wc-connect">→ More storms mean more chances for water to reach the tracks. Amtrak recorded more than 450 weather-related disruptions from 2006 to 2019.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="weather-card wc-intensity">
          <p class="wc-title">Flooding now comes from both stronger storms and rising water.</p>
          <div class="compound-scene" role="img" aria-label="Cross-section showing the Amtrak rail corridor squeezed between heavier storms above and rising seas below">
            <div class="cs-sky">
              <div class="cs-rain"></div>
              <span class="cs-badge cs-badge-top">↓ Storms: +55% more intense</span>
            </div>
            <div class="cs-track-zone">
              <div class="cs-rail"></div>
              <div class="cs-ties"></div>
              <div class="cs-rail"></div>
            </div>
            <div class="cs-flood-zone">
              <span class="cs-badge cs-badge-bot">↑ Sea level rising — Wilmington #1 hot spot</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="wc-connect">→ A restored living shoreline at Fox Point can help with both problems by slowing runoff and softening wave action before water reaches the rail edge.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="weather-card wc-heat">
          <p class="wc-title">Hotter summers will put more stress on the rail line.</p>
          <div class="wc-thermo-compare">
            <div class="wc-thermo-item">
              <div class="thermo-wrap">
                <div class="thermo"><div class="thermo-fill tf-now"></div></div>
                <div class="thermo-bulb tb-now"></div>
              </div>
              <span class="wc-year">Now</span>
            </div>
            <div class="wc-thermo-item">
              <div class="thermo-wrap">
                <div class="thermo"><div class="thermo-fill tf-2050"></div></div>
                <div class="thermo-bulb tb-2050"></div>
              </div>
              <span class="wc-year wc-year-now">2050</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="wc-stat-num">+4–5°F</p>
          <p class="wc-connect">→ Extreme heat can damage rails and signals. Restored wetland plants at Fox Point can help cool the corridor edge.</p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <p class="source-note section-source">Sources: Amtrak Climate Vulnerability Assessment (2022); Amtrak Climate Resilience Strategic Plan (2022); NEC Climate Pilot Adaptation Plan (2017)</p>
    </section>

    <section class="panel precedent-section" id="precedent">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div>
          <p class="section-label">Precedent</p>
          <h2>The model is built.<br />We can borrow it.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="section-copy">Fox Point and the Hudson Highlands share the harder version of a shoreline-restoration problem — a thin strip of riverfront wedged between an active passenger rail line on one side and a highway on the other, with rising water and limited public access. The Hudson Highlands Fjord Trail (HHFT) shows the model can be built.</p>
      </div>

      <figure class="precedent-figure">
        <img
          src="/assets/precedent-hhft-rendering.jpg"
          alt="Hudson Highlands Fjord Trail design rendering: a gravel shared-use path along the Hudson River shoreline with a boulder edge stabilizing the bank, a long wood bench, and a planted buffer separating walkers and cyclists from the rail corridor."
          class="precedent-figure-image"
          width="768"
          height="501"
          loading="lazy"
          decoding="async"
        />
        <figcaption class="precedent-figure-caption">
          Hudson Highlands Fjord Trail · design rendering. Boulder edge, expanded trail, planted buffer — the same toolkit Fox Point needs.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>

      <div class="precedent-grid">
        <article class="corridor-brief-card">
          <p class="corridor-brief-eyebrow">Hudson Highlands Fjord Trail</p>
          <ul class="precedent-list">
            <li>Hudson River shoreline</li>
            <li>Metro-North Hudson Line</li>
            <li>NY State Route 9D</li>
            <li>Restoring access + shoreline resilience</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
        <article class="corridor-brief-card precedent-card-here">
          <p class="corridor-brief-eyebrow">Claymont → Fox Point</p>
          <ul class="precedent-list">
            <li>Delaware River shoreline</li>
            <li>Amtrak Northeast Corridor</li>
            <li>Interstate 495</li>
            <li>Restoring access + shoreline resilience</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>

      <p class="source-note section-source">Source: <a class="precedent-link" href="https://hhft.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">hhft.org</a></p>
    </section>

    <section class="photo-section" id="site">
      <div class="photo-header">
        <p class="section-label">Site Readiness</p>
        <h2>Phase 1 restores the cove. The vision reconnects the shoreline to the Claymont Transit Center.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="photo-card">
        <svg
          class="site-schematic site-schematic--landscape"
          viewBox="0 0 1200 520"
          preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet"
          role="img"
          aria-labelledby="schematic-title schematic-desc"
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
        >
          <title id="schematic-title">Schematic of the Claymont-to-Fox-Point shoreline reconnection</title>
          <desc id="schematic-desc">A ribbon schematic of a roughly three-mile shoreline corridor running south from the Claymont Transit Center. The top two-thirds of the ribbon shows the long-term reconnection vision, about two miles of shoreline not yet built. The bottom third shows the existing Fox Point Riverview Trail, about one mile already in place. Inside the existing-trail segment, Fox Point Cove is highlighted in orange as Phase 1, a 2.7-acre wetland restoration with $5M in pledges. The Amtrak Northeast Corridor rail line runs inland of the ribbon; the Delaware River forms its eastern edge.</desc>

          <rect x="0" y="0" width="1200" height="520" fill="#f2eee5"/>
          <defs>
            <pattern id="landTexture" width="14" height="14" patternUnits="userSpaceOnUse" patternTransform="rotate(35)">
              <line x1="0" y1="0" x2="0" y2="14" stroke="#d6e1d4" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.55"/>
            </pattern>
            <pattern id="waterTexture" width="60" height="22" patternUnits="userSpaceOnUse">
              <path d="M 0 11 Q 15 4 30 11 T 60 11" fill="none" stroke="#a8c5d8" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.55"/>
            </pattern>
          </defs>
          <rect x="0" y="0" width="1200" height="520" fill="url(#landTexture)"/>

          <rect x="880" y="0" width="320" height="520" fill="#cbdfe8"/>
          <rect x="880" y="0" width="320" height="520" fill="url(#waterTexture)"/>
          <line x1="880" y1="0" x2="880" y2="520" stroke="#12362a" stroke-width="2" opacity="0.5"/>

          <line x1="180" y1="60" x2="180" y2="475" stroke="#8a8475" stroke-width="6" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0.4"/>
          <line x1="340" y1="60" x2="340" y2="475" stroke="#1a1a1a" stroke-width="3" stroke-dasharray="12 8" opacity="0.7"/>

          <rect x="540" y="80" width="180" height="265" fill="#ebe6d8" stroke="#b59a76" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-dasharray="7 5"/>

          <rect x="540" y="345" width="180" height="130" fill="#d8e7d7" stroke="#3a6e44" stroke-width="2.5"/>

          <rect x="510" y="380" width="240" height="62" fill="rgba(200, 116, 66, 0.22)" stroke="#c87442" stroke-width="2.5"/>

          <g transform="translate(630, 80)">
            <circle r="13" fill="#12362a" stroke="#fffaf2" stroke-width="2.5"/>
            <rect x="-6" y="-5" width="12" height="9" rx="1.5" fill="#fffaf2"/>
            <line x1="-4" y1="2" x2="-4" y2="4" stroke="#12362a" stroke-width="1.2"/>
            <line x1="4" y1="2" x2="4" y2="4" stroke="#12362a" stroke-width="1.2"/>
          </g>

          <circle cx="630" cy="475" r="6" fill="#8a8475" stroke="#fffaf2" stroke-width="1.5"/>

          <g font-family="Avenir Next, Segoe UI, sans-serif">
            <text x="630" y="40" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label" font-size="15" letter-spacing="1.5">CLAYMONT TRANSIT CENTER</text>
            <text x="630" y="58" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-sublabel" font-size="11" font-weight="600" fill="#607063" letter-spacing="0.6">SEPTA · Amtrak</text>

            <text x="630" y="200" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label" font-size="14" font-weight="800" fill="#7a5a30" letter-spacing="1.2">LONG-TERM RECONNECTION</text>
            <text x="630" y="220" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-sublabel" font-size="11" font-weight="600" fill="#7a5a30" letter-spacing="0.6">~ 2 mi · shoreline not yet built</text>

            <text x="630" y="367" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label" font-size="13" font-weight="800" fill="#3a6e44" letter-spacing="0.8">EXISTING TRAIL · ~ 1 MI</text>

            <text x="630" y="406" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label site-schematic-label--accent" font-size="14" font-weight="800" letter-spacing="0.5">PHASE 1 — FOX POINT COVE</text>
            <text x="630" y="424" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-sublabel" font-size="11" font-weight="600" fill="#7a3e22">$5M pledged · 2.7-acre wetland restoration</text>

            <text x="630" y="500" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-sublabel" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#5b574e" letter-spacing="0.6">EDGEMOOR ↓</text>

            <text x="340" y="50" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label site-schematic-label--rail" font-size="13">Amtrak NEC rail</text>

            <text x="1040" y="440" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label site-schematic-label--water" font-size="18" letter-spacing="2">DELAWARE</text>
            <text x="1040" y="465" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label site-schematic-label--water" font-size="18" letter-spacing="2">RIVER</text>
          </g>
        </svg>

        <svg
          class="site-schematic site-schematic--portrait"
          viewBox="0 0 400 600"
          preserveAspectRatio="xMidYMid meet"
          aria-hidden="true"
          focusable="false"
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
        >
          <rect x="0" y="0" width="400" height="600" fill="#f2eee5"/>
          <defs>
            <pattern id="landTextureP" width="14" height="14" patternUnits="userSpaceOnUse" patternTransform="rotate(35)">
              <line x1="0" y1="0" x2="0" y2="14" stroke="#d6e1d4" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.55"/>
            </pattern>
            <pattern id="waterTextureP" width="40" height="22" patternUnits="userSpaceOnUse">
              <path d="M 0 11 Q 10 4 20 11 T 40 11" fill="none" stroke="#a8c5d8" stroke-width="1" opacity="0.55"/>
            </pattern>
          </defs>
          <rect x="0" y="0" width="400" height="600" fill="url(#landTextureP)"/>

          <rect x="320" y="0" width="80" height="600" fill="#cbdfe8"/>
          <rect x="320" y="0" width="80" height="600" fill="url(#waterTextureP)"/>
          <line x1="320" y1="0" x2="320" y2="600" stroke="#12362a" stroke-width="2" opacity="0.5"/>

          <line x1="50" y1="80" x2="50" y2="560" stroke="#8a8475" stroke-width="5" stroke-linecap="round" opacity="0.4"/>
          <line x1="115" y1="80" x2="115" y2="560" stroke="#1a1a1a" stroke-width="2.5" stroke-dasharray="10 6" opacity="0.7"/>

          <rect x="190" y="80" width="90" height="320" fill="#ebe6d8" stroke="#b59a76" stroke-width="2" stroke-dasharray="6 4"/>
          <rect x="190" y="400" width="90" height="160" fill="#d8e7d7" stroke="#3a6e44" stroke-width="2"/>
          <rect x="170" y="445" width="130" height="70" fill="rgba(200, 116, 66, 0.22)" stroke="#c87442" stroke-width="2"/>

          <g transform="translate(235, 80)">
            <circle r="11" fill="#12362a" stroke="#fffaf2" stroke-width="2"/>
            <rect x="-5" y="-4" width="10" height="7" rx="1.2" fill="#fffaf2"/>
            <line x1="-3" y1="2" x2="-3" y2="3.5" stroke="#12362a" stroke-width="1"/>
            <line x1="3" y1="2" x2="3" y2="3.5" stroke="#12362a" stroke-width="1"/>
          </g>

          <circle cx="235" cy="560" r="5" fill="#8a8475" stroke="#fffaf2" stroke-width="1.2"/>

          <g transform="translate(370, 32)">
            <circle r="18" fill="#fffaf2" stroke="#12362a" stroke-width="1.5"/>
            <path d="M 0 -11 L 3 2 L 0 -2 L -3 2 Z" fill="#12362a"/>
            <text y="0" text-anchor="middle" font-family="Avenir Next, Segoe UI, sans-serif" font-size="9" font-weight="800" fill="#12362a">N</text>
          </g>

          <g font-family="Avenir Next, Segoe UI, sans-serif">
            <text x="235" y="42" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label" font-size="12" font-weight="800" letter-spacing="0.8">CLAYMONT TRANSIT</text>
            <text x="235" y="58" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label" font-size="12" font-weight="800" letter-spacing="0.8">CENTER</text>

            <text x="235" y="225" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label" font-size="12" font-weight="800" fill="#7a5a30" letter-spacing="0.8">LONG-TERM</text>
            <text x="235" y="242" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label" font-size="12" font-weight="800" fill="#7a5a30" letter-spacing="0.8">RECONNECTION</text>
            <text x="235" y="262" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-sublabel" font-size="10" font-weight="600" fill="#7a5a30">~ 2 mi · not yet built</text>

            <text x="235" y="423" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label" font-size="11" font-weight="800" fill="#3a6e44" letter-spacing="0.7">EXISTING TRAIL · ~ 1 MI</text>

            <text x="235" y="473" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label site-schematic-label--accent" font-size="12" font-weight="800" letter-spacing="0.3">PHASE 1 — COVE</text>
            <text x="235" y="490" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-sublabel" font-size="10" font-weight="600" fill="#7a3e22">$5M pledged</text>
            <text x="235" y="504" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-sublabel" font-size="10" font-weight="600" fill="#7a3e22">2.7-acre wetland</text>

            <text x="235" y="585" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-sublabel" font-size="11" font-weight="700" fill="#5b574e" letter-spacing="0.6">EDGEMOOR ↓</text>

            <text x="115" y="68" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label site-schematic-label--rail" font-size="11">Amtrak NEC</text>

            <text x="360" y="290" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label site-schematic-label--water" font-size="14" letter-spacing="1.5">DELAWARE</text>
            <text x="360" y="308" text-anchor="middle" class="site-schematic-label site-schematic-label--water" font-size="14" letter-spacing="1.5">RIVER</text>
          </g>
        </svg>

        <div class="photo-overlay">
          <div class="photo-badge">
            <p class="photo-badge-title">Phase 1 — Fox Point Cove</p>
            <p>$5M pledged and a state plan in place for a 2.7-acre wetland restoration. The long-term vision continues the shoreline about 2 miles north to the Claymont Transit Center.</p>
            <a class="photo-trail-link" href="https://delawaregreenways.org/trail/fox-point-riverview-trail/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">See the existing trail →</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="site-chips">
        <span>Phase 1 funded · $5M pledged</span>
        <span>2.7 acres of wetland restoration</span>
        <span>Existing trail · ~ 1 mi</span>
        <span>Long-term reconnection · ~ 2 mi</span>
        <span>203 river acres in scope</span>
        <span>Delaware Greenways trail partner</span>
        <span>Established state park</span>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="panel corridor-section">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div>
          <p class="section-label">Project Readiness</p>
          <h2>Delaware already wrote the Fox Point plan.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="section-copy">This is not just a big idea. The state has already named the site, outlined the work, and shown the next steps.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="corridor-brief-grid">
        <article class="corridor-brief-card">
          <p class="corridor-brief-eyebrow">State Status</p>
          <p>Delaware’s environmental agency, DNREC, already lists this as a managed cleanup area. The project area covers about 203 river acres across 1.4 miles, including Fox Point Cove.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="corridor-brief-card">
          <p class="corridor-brief-eyebrow">Planned Work</p>
          <p>The state plan calls for marsh restoration at Fox Point Cove, including invasive plant removal, shoreline grading, clean fill, native planting, wave-break structures, and erosion control near Stoney Creek Wharf.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="corridor-brief-card">
          <p class="corridor-brief-eyebrow">Next Steps</p>
          <p>The plan already covers about 2.7 acres of wetland work. Next comes engineering, permits, construction, and three years of follow-up monitoring.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="panel capital-section" id="funding">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div>
          <p class="section-label">Funding</p>
          <h2>Fox Point already has $5 million in pledges.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="section-copy">This site does not need a new pitch. It needs design, permits, planning, and people working together so the money already linked to Fox Point can be put to work.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="capital-stack">
        <article class="capital-row">
          <div class="capital-meta">
            <p class="capital-amount">$2.5M</p>
            <p class="capital-source">Heffernan Bond Bill</p>
            <span class="status-chip status-contingent">Not active yet</span>
          </div>
          <div class="capital-detail">
            <h3>Wetland and park work</h3>
            <p>Rep. Heffernan pledged $3M in bond funding to help meet state environmental requirements for the new Edgemoor port. Of that, $2.5M is set aside for wetland and park work at Fox Point. It would move when port construction starts and the Diamond State Port Corporation approves it.</p>
            <div class="capital-bar-track">
